<subSubSection id="3C157A1F33391F3F4D48F64C0F6E7C0D" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="D89A65FE9B6647CF85F6F7D39420B16E" pageNumber="35">The species in this genus are seed-harvesting ants, whose nest mounds are often conspicuously decorated with pebbles. The workers are diurnal and have a potent sting.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9D58F30981AF9AC54DDE827650504462" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="56325F5D72965E09806632F7DCDCADE0" pageNumber="35">
Several of the taxa belong to difficult complexes, and species boundaries remain unclear. In neighboring Arizona a series of stabilized hybrid lineages has been documented in the 
<taxonomicName id="E173CDBE4C510C8FD2DE63C7765148A5" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34335" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pogonomyrmex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pogonomyrmex barbatus (Smith)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barbatus">P. barbatus-complex</taxonomicName>
(Helms Cahan et al. 2002).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2B56D5D3EEDDA0135134AEC4CF5CE295" pageNumber="35">
